Step 1
Standardize the variable by applying scale; and assign them into dataframe

d$K <- scale(d$kcal.per.g)
d$N <- scale(d$neocortex.perc)
d$M <- scale(log(d$mass))  # here's a log


Step 1-2 optional
Drop missing value (NA) using complete.cases

dcc <- d[complete.cases(d$k, d$N, d$M), ]


Step 2
Build the model by applying quap

m5.5_draft <- quap(
  alist(
    K ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a + bN*N,        # linear relationship
    a ~ dnorm(0, 1),       # we guess prior and its distribution
    bN ~ dnorm(0, 1),      # also based on guess
    sigma ~ dexp(1)
  ), data = dcc
)


Step 3-1
Extract priors from our model using extract.prior

prior <- extract.prior(m5.5_draft)


Step 3-2
Plot prior predictive distribution / prior prediction

xseq <- c(-2, 2) # define the limit of x-axis
mu <- link(m5.5_draft, post=prior, data=list(N=xseq))  # calculate the distribution by giving  model, prior, and data

# plot
plot(NULL, xlim=xseq, ylim=xseq)     # create figure

for (i in 1:50) lines(               # plot N of lines using for loop
        xseq,                        # data point
        mu[i, ],                     # each combination of two points
        col=col.alpha("black", 0.3)  # specify the color
        )

The result is not informative, lets revise our prior


Step 4-1
Revise prior to see if the prior prediction looks more reasonable

m5.5 <- quap(
  alist(
    K ~ dnorm(mu, sigma),
    mu <- a + bN*N,        
    a ~ dnorm(0, 0.2),       # revise the sigma to 0.2 from 1
    bN ~ dnorm(0, 0.5),      # revise the sigma to 0.5 from 1
    sigma ~ dexp(1)
  ), data = dcc
)


Step 4-2
Plot the prior prediction with revised prior

prior <- extract.prior(m5.5)
xseq <- c(-2, 2) # define the limit of x-axis
mu <- link(m5.5, post=prior, data=list(N=xseq))  # calculate the distribution by giving  model, prior, and data

# plot
plot(NULL, xlim=xseq, ylim=xseq)     # create figure

for (i in 1:50) lines(               # plot N of lines using for loop
        xseq,                        # data point
        mu[i, ],                     # each combination of two points
        col=col.alpha("black", 0.3)  # specify the color
        )


Step 5
Compare the result of prior prediction to see which prior is more reasonable /sensible

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
xseq <- c(-2, 2) # define the limit of x-axis
# first plot
prior <- extract.prior(m5.5_draft)
mu <- link(m5.5_draft, post=prior, data=list(N=xseq))  
plot(NULL, xlim=xseq, ylim=xseq)     # create figure
for (i in 1:50) lines(               # plot N of lines using for loop
        xseq,                        # data point
        mu[i, ],                     # each combination of two points
        col=col.alpha("black", 0.3)  # specify the color
        )

# second plot
prior <- extract.prior(m5.5)

plot(NULL, xlim=xseq, ylim=xseq)     # create figure

for (i in 1:50) lines(               # plot N of lines using for loop
        xseq,                        # data point
        mu[i, ],                     # each combination of two points

        )


posterior

xseq <- seq( from=min(dcc$N)-0.15 , to=max(dcc$N)+0.15 , length.out=30 )
mu <- link( m5.5 , data=list(N=xseq) )
mu_mean <- apply(mu,2,mean)
mu_PI <- apply(mu,2,PI)
plot( K ~ N , data=dcc )
lines( xseq , mu_mean , lwd=2 )
shade( mu_PI , xseq )
